<td><img src="media/dwr-logo-200.gif"/></td>

<td width="300px">
<h1 style="font-size:150%;">Direct Web Remoting</h1>
<p>DWR is a Java library that enables Java on the server and JavaScript in a browser to interact and call each other as simply as possible.</p>
<p><strong>DWR is Easy Ajax for Java</strong></p>
</td>

</tr>
</table>

<p><strong>DWR version 3.0.rc1</strong> is the most recent development release. <strong>DWR version 2.0</strong> is the current stable release. <a href="downloads/index.html">Download them now</a> and <a href="introduction/getting-started.html">use DWR in your website in minutes</a>.</p>

<div style="text-align:center;">
<a class="nolink" href="introduction/index.html"><img src="media/front-about2.png" alt="Introduction"/></a>&nbsp;<a class="nolink" href="downloads/index.html"><img src="media/front-download2.png" alt="Download"/></a> <a class="nolink" href="documentation/index.html"><img src="media/front-documentation2.png" alt="Documentation"/></a>&nbsp;<a class="nolink" href="support/index.html"><img src="media/front-support2.png" alt="Support"/></a>
</div>

<p><strong>DWR</strong> will generate the JavaScript to allow <strong>web browsers to securely call into Java code</strong> almost as if it was running locally. It can <strong>marshal virtually any data</strong> including collections, POJOs, XML and binary data like images and PDF files. All that is required is a security policy that defines what is allowed.</p>

<p>With <strong>Reverse Ajax</strong>, DWR allows Java code running on a server to use client side APIs to publish updates to arbitrary groups of browsers. This allows interaction 2 ways - <strong>browser calling server and server calling browser</strong>. DWR supports Comet, Polling and Piggyback (sending data in with normal requests) as ways to publish to browsers.</p>

<p>DWR provides integration with <a href="documentation/server/integration/spring.html">Spring</a>, <a href="documentation/server/integration/struts.html">Struts</a>, <a href="documentation/server/integration/guice.html">Guice</a>, <a href="documentation/server/integration/hibernate.html">Hibernate</a> and others.</p>

<p>DWR is Open Source, available under the <a href="http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html">Apache Software License v2</a>.</p>

</div>
